elation for ellipticals in clusters is significantly flatter than observed at bright magnitudes (although the scatter is about right), and the model predicts galaxy circular velocities, at a given luminosity, that are about 30per cent larger than is observed. It is unclear whether these discrepancies represent fundamental shortcomings of the model, or whether they result from the various approximations and uncertainties inherent in the technique. Our more detailed methods do not change our earlier conclusion that just over half the stars in the Universe are expected to have formed since [dN/dM$_{1}$] [df$_{12}$/dt$_{1}$] [M$_{2}$/M$_{1}$] dt$_{1}$ (M$_{1}$ $\lt$ M$_{2}$). z $\lt$\~{}1.5.},
  doi      = {10.1046/j.1365-8711.2000.03879.x},
